WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.712 --> 00:00:08.570
-Good morning.

00:00:08.570 --> 00:00:20.280
Welcome to Radcliffe Day 2016.

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:24.330
This is a day to celebrate
Radcliffe's past, present

00:00:24.330 --> 00:00:25.810
and future.

00:00:25.810 --> 00:00:28.220
I'm Liz Cohen, I'm Dean
of the Radcliffe Institute

00:00:28.220 --> 00:00:29.950
for Advanced Study.

00:00:29.950 --> 00:00:34.460
Being here among so many of you
who are celebrating reunions

00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:39.461
has reminded me that I mark
a milestone of my own--

00:00:39.461 --> 00:00:41.570
my fifth year as Radcliffe dean.

00:00:48.170 --> 00:00:52.060
And what a whirlwind these
five years have been.

00:00:52.060 --> 00:00:56.090
I've enjoyed watching our
three core programs grow.

00:00:56.090 --> 00:01:00.000
Our very competitive fellowship
program, our exciting public

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.730
lectures and conferences
through academic ventures,

00:01:03.730 --> 00:01:07.350
and our renowned Schlesinger
Library on the history of women

00:01:07.350 --> 00:01:08.730
in America.

00:01:08.730 --> 00:01:12.030
I've also taken great pleasure
in expanding the Radcliffe

00:01:12.030 --> 00:01:15.810
professorship program to
help Harvard schools recruit

00:01:15.810 --> 00:01:20.220
new diverse faculty talent,
deepening the institute's

00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:23.890
integration of the arts
in its programming,

00:01:23.890 --> 00:01:26.880
and creating new
opportunities for students

00:01:26.880 --> 00:01:32.440
to partake in advanced study
beyond the standard curriculum.

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:37.480
A high point of this year, as
other years in the recent past,

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:42.250
is honoring an inspiring woman
with the Radcliffe medal.

00:01:42.250 --> 00:01:46.660
We lauded Supreme Court Justice
Ruth Bader Ginsburg last year,

00:01:46.660 --> 00:01:52.890
and Harvard president Drew
Faust in 2014, just to name two.

00:01:52.890 --> 00:01:57.100
Today we are delighted
that our Radcliffe medalist

00:01:57.100 --> 00:01:59.770
Janet Yellen, Chair
of the Federal Reserve

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:02.052
Board of the United States.

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:18.950
It is our tradition to begin
Radcliffe Day with a panel

00:02:18.950 --> 00:02:24.450
discussion on a topic close to
our honoree's head and heart.

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:28.320
At lunch, we will celebrate
Janet Yellen's achievements,

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:31.700
but now we will pay her
the honor of digging

00:02:31.700 --> 00:02:35.240
into the subject she
cares deeply about.

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:40.460
That topic is how to build an
American economy for prosperity

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:42.160
and equality.

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:48.220
How to promote vigorous economic
growth that is broadly shared.

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:51.050
In many ways, this
past century has

00:02:51.050 --> 00:02:53.680
brought remarkable advances.

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:59.490
In 1916, average life expectancy
hovered around age 50,

00:02:59.490 --> 00:03:02.060
for both men and women
in the United States.

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:04.850
Now, it is well above 70.

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:07.550
Today, most citizens'
working lives

00:03:07.550 --> 00:03:10.580
involve shorter hours and
fewer life-threatening

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:14.230
hazards than our
forebears faced.

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:17.970
Roughly 63% of us
own our own homes,

00:03:17.970 --> 00:03:21.880
compared to less than
half of Americans in 1916,

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:26.700
even if today's rate is slightly
lower than it was a decade ago.

00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:31.080
We all enjoy recreational and
entertainment opportunities

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:34.410
beyond our grandparents'
imaginations.

00:03:34.410 --> 00:03:37.180
For many of you sitting
in the audience today,

00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:39.750
and the ability to travel
to Cambridge to enjoy

00:03:39.750 --> 00:03:43.150
this panel would have
been far out of reach.

00:03:43.150 --> 00:03:47.440
And watching it online would
have been unfathomable.

00:03:47.440 --> 00:03:51.580
While we mark enormous
societal progress,

00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:56.740
Americans' equal access to
a better economic standard

00:03:56.740 --> 00:03:58.780
of living is shrinking.

00:03:58.780 --> 00:04:03.620
We live in an era notable for
stunning growth in inequality.

00:04:03.620 --> 00:04:08.380
Right now, the world's
wealthiest 62 individuals

00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:12.850
own more wealth than the bottom
50 percent of the entire world

00:04:12.850 --> 00:04:14.710
population.

00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:19.990
Just since 2010, the fortunes
of those 62 individuals

00:04:19.990 --> 00:04:23.080
have increased by more than
half a trillion dollars.

00:04:23.080 --> 00:04:25.750
While the wealth of
the bottom 50% percent

00:04:25.750 --> 00:04:28.850
has fallen by a full
trillion dollars,

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:32.930
which constitutes a drop of 38%.

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:35.790
The United States is
by no means insulated

00:04:35.790 --> 00:04:37.660
from this global trend.

00:04:37.660 --> 00:04:40.970
According to a report by the
Economic Policy Institute,

00:04:40.970 --> 00:04:45.860
since the 1970s real
wages for the top 1%

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:51.030
have risen 362%, while
real wages for most workers

00:04:51.030 --> 00:04:52.740
have stagnated.

00:04:52.740 --> 00:04:56.340
The predictable result has been
increased wealth concentration

00:04:56.340 --> 00:04:57.620
at the top.

00:04:57.620 --> 00:05:03.660
In 2014, the wealthiest 20% of
Americans owned more than 80%

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:05.600
of all American wealth.

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:09.070
In contrast, the wealth
of the poorest 20%

00:05:09.070 --> 00:05:11.470
was negative, meaning
that they owed

00:05:11.470 --> 00:05:16.300
more money than the value of all
of their assets put together.

00:05:16.300 --> 00:05:21.010
Despite the tendency of a
whopping 87% of Americans

00:05:21.010 --> 00:05:24.400
to identify themselves
as middle class,

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:29.490
the Pew Research Center issued
a report at the end of 2015,

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:33.500
with its main finding
stated clearly in the title.

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:36.800
The report was called,
The American Middle Class

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:41.380
is Losing Ground-- No Longer
The Majority and Falling Behind

00:05:41.380 --> 00:05:42.980
Financially.

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:47.100
Scholars and commentators
of all political persuasions

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:49.310
have expressed alarm.

00:05:49.310 --> 00:05:52.100
Alan Greenspan, former
chair of the Federal Reserve

00:05:52.100 --> 00:05:54.820
Board-- appointed by
President Ronald Reagan--

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:59.030
has said publicly that current
levels of inequality are,

00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:01.620
and I quote him, "not
the type of thing

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:06.200
which a democratic society, a
capitalist democratic society,

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:09.670
can really accept
without addressing."

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:11.990
Elsewhere on the
political spectrum,

00:06:11.990 --> 00:06:14.600
economists and public
policy experts--

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:18.320
like Paul Krugman, Joseph
Stiglitz, and Robert Putnam--

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:20.880
likewise worried that
the growing chasm

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:25.100
between haves and have nots
threatens the very foundation

00:06:25.100 --> 00:06:27.650
of American democracy.

00:06:27.650 --> 00:06:30.440
At the beginning of this
year, officials from the World

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:32.870
Bank at the International
Monetary Fund,

00:06:32.870 --> 00:06:36.000
along with former Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.130
all issued statements
within days of each other.

00:06:39.130 --> 00:06:42.620
Identifying inequality
as a chief impediment

00:06:42.620 --> 00:06:45.540
to sustained economic growth.

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:48.690
It wasn't always this way.

00:06:48.690 --> 00:06:53.850
Even as recently as the three
decades following World War II.

00:06:53.850 --> 00:06:58.070
Wearing my other hat as a
20th century US historian,

00:06:58.070 --> 00:07:00.990
I wrote a book entitled
A Consumer's Republic,

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:05.620
The Politics of Mass
Consumption in Post-war America.

00:07:05.620 --> 00:07:08.310
There I showed that
the post-war order,

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:11.090
that I labeled a
consumer's republic,

00:07:11.090 --> 00:07:14.600
was built upon an assumption
that was widely shared

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:17.830
by labor, , business and
government officials.

00:07:17.830 --> 00:07:21.020
That broad based
economic prosperity

00:07:21.020 --> 00:07:25.730
would benefit individuals and
the nation at the same time,

00:07:25.730 --> 00:07:29.320
as mass consumers protected
the jobs and purchasing

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:32.060
power of their fellow citizens.

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:34.970
President Harry Truman
made this point often.

00:07:34.970 --> 00:07:37.980
To quote directly from one
of his speeches in 1950,

00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:41.200
Truman said, "raising the
standards of our poorest

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:45.170
families will not be at the
expense of anybody else.

00:07:45.170 --> 00:07:47.510
We will all benefit
from doing it,

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:51.460
for the incomes of the rest of
us will rise at the same time."

00:07:51.460 --> 00:07:52.590
End quote.

00:07:52.590 --> 00:07:55.720
Moreover, Truman and
subsequent presidents

00:07:55.720 --> 00:07:58.580
believed that an
economically secure,

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:03.330
more equitable citizenry was
capitalism's best defense

00:08:03.330 --> 00:08:07.270
against communism in
the raging Cold War.

00:08:07.270 --> 00:08:11.580
So how did we get
from then to now?

00:08:11.580 --> 00:08:14.500
And what can we do about it?

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:17.020
These are the questions
that our esteemed panel

00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:18.720
will consider today.

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:21.570
The panel be moderated
by Cecilia Rouse,

00:08:21.570 --> 00:08:24.100
the dean of the Woodrow
Wilson School of Public Policy

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:27.230
at Princeton University,
where she is also

00:08:27.230 --> 00:08:30.890
the Lawrence and Shirley
Katzman and Lewis and Anna Ernst

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:34.020
Professor in the
Economics of Education,

00:08:34.020 --> 00:08:37.539
and a Professor of Economics
and Public Affairs.

00:08:37.539 --> 00:08:40.470
She served on President Bill
Clinton's National Economic

00:08:40.470 --> 00:08:43.150
Council, and as a member
of the White House

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:47.520
Council of Economic Advisers
under President Barack Obama.

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:50.940
She earned her A.B.
in Economics in 1986,

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:55.970
and her PhD in Economics in
1992, both here at Harvard.

00:08:55.970 --> 00:08:58.460
Dean Rouse will introduce
the other panelists.

00:08:58.460 --> 00:09:02.180
Please join me in warmly
welcoming Dean Cecilia Rouse.

00:09:14.500 --> 00:09:16.200
-So, good morning.

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:18.170
It's an absolute
pleasure to introduce

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:21.320
this morning's panel, Building
an Economy for Prosperity

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:22.790
and Equality.

00:09:22.790 --> 00:09:25.170
It's quite a fitting
topic for a panel convened

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:27.050
in honor of Janet
Yellen's selection

00:09:27.050 --> 00:09:29.384
as this year's
Radcliffe medalist.

00:09:29.384 --> 00:09:30.800
As you'll hear
throughout the day,

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:32.300
Janet's professional
life has been

00:09:32.300 --> 00:09:36.120
devoted to studying critical
issues facing the macroeconomy,

00:09:36.120 --> 00:09:38.400
both through her writings
as an academic scholar

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:40.750
and through her public
service, particularly

00:09:40.750 --> 00:09:42.680
in the Federal Reserve System.

00:09:42.680 --> 00:09:45.200
She's been a key player in
maintaining and promoting

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:47.490
the economic health
of our country,

00:09:47.490 --> 00:09:49.830
primarily by
working to find ways

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:54.170
to maximize employment,
stabilize prices, and moderate

00:09:54.170 --> 00:09:58.050
long term interest rates
through monetary policy.

00:09:58.050 --> 00:09:59.810
However, in recent
years that task

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:02.610
has gotten just a
wee bit trickier.

00:10:02.610 --> 00:10:05.620
For decades, economists
promoted overall economic growth

00:10:05.620 --> 00:10:09.030
with the belief that a
rising tide lifts all boats.

00:10:09.030 --> 00:10:11.690
That is, that the fruits and
gains from economic growth

00:10:11.690 --> 00:10:14.150
would be shared by all.

00:10:14.150 --> 00:10:16.130
This view is perhaps
not surprising,

00:10:16.130 --> 00:10:19.340
since between about
1910 and 1950,

00:10:19.340 --> 00:10:23.030
wage inequality actually
narrowed, and then remained

00:10:23.030 --> 00:10:25.870
relatively stable
until about 1980.

00:10:25.870 --> 00:10:28.360
It is pretty clear, however,
that today all boats

00:10:28.360 --> 00:10:31.060
are not rising together.

00:10:31.060 --> 00:10:34.650
The past 35 years has seen
tremendous economic growth,

00:10:34.650 --> 00:10:39.250
but also an incredible rise in
income and wealth inequality.

00:10:39.250 --> 00:10:44.540
From 1973 to 2005, the top
1/5 of real family income

00:10:44.540 --> 00:10:47.850
increased by about
1.6% annually,

00:10:47.850 --> 00:10:49.320
while the bottom
fifth of families

00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:51.740
experienced almost no gains.

00:10:51.740 --> 00:10:57.800
In 1978, the top 0.1% of
families held 7% of all wealth,

00:10:57.800 --> 00:11:03.370
while they held three times
that much-- 22%-- in 2012.

00:11:03.370 --> 00:11:06.040
In fact, today we have
levels of inequality

00:11:06.040 --> 00:11:09.250
that have not been seen since
the times of the robber barons

00:11:09.250 --> 00:11:12.490
over a century ago, with
rather dire consequences

00:11:12.490 --> 00:11:16.380
for our economic, political,
and social fabric.

00:11:16.380 --> 00:11:18.370
So the speakers on
today's panel will

00:11:18.370 --> 00:11:20.720
help illuminate what
we know and don't

00:11:20.720 --> 00:11:23.670
know about economic growth
over the past century,

00:11:23.670 --> 00:11:26.790
and how it has
been shared or not.

00:11:26.790 --> 00:11:28.600
They will also highlight
some of the causes

00:11:28.600 --> 00:11:32.620
for the increased inequality,
and perhaps-- just perhaps--

00:11:32.620 --> 00:11:35.310
offer a way to address it.

00:11:35.310 --> 00:11:36.810
After giving each
of our panelists

00:11:36.810 --> 00:11:39.090
a few minutes to discuss
an important dimension

00:11:39.090 --> 00:11:42.080
of this issue, the panel will
have a short conversation

00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:44.680
before we open it up
to your questions.

00:11:44.680 --> 00:11:47.320
So let me introduce
our illustrious panel.

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:49.840
First up is David
Autor, a professor

00:11:49.840 --> 00:11:52.700
and associate department
chair at the MIT Department

00:11:52.700 --> 00:11:54.120
of Economics.

00:11:54.120 --> 00:11:56.660
David is a faculty research
associate of the National

00:11:56.660 --> 00:11:59.790
Bureau of Economic Research,
and a former Editor-in-Chief

00:11:59.790 --> 00:12:02.310
of the Journal of
Economic Perspectives.

00:12:02.310 --> 00:12:04.530
His current fields
of specialization

00:12:04.530 --> 00:12:07.320
include human capital
and earnings inequality,

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:09.690
labor market impact of
technological change

00:12:09.690 --> 00:12:13.360
and globalization, disability
insurance, and labor supply,

00:12:13.360 --> 00:12:17.700
and temporary help and
other intermediated work

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:18.910
arrangements.

00:12:18.910 --> 00:12:21.080
He received his Bachelor's
Degree in Psychology

00:12:21.080 --> 00:12:24.200
from Tufts University,
and a PhD In Public Policy

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:26.860
from the Harvard Kennedy
School of Government.

00:12:26.860 --> 00:12:29.880
Next to speak will be Louise
Sheiner, a senior fellow

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:32.910
in Economic Studies, and policy
director for the Hutchins

00:12:32.910 --> 00:12:36.240
Center on Fiscal and Monetary
Policy at the Brookings

00:12:36.240 --> 00:12:38.390
Institution.

00:12:38.390 --> 00:12:41.390
Prior to joining Brookings,
Louise served as an economist

00:12:41.390 --> 00:12:45.060
with the board of governors
at the Federal Reserve System.

00:12:45.060 --> 00:12:47.350
Most recently, as
the senior economist

00:12:47.350 --> 00:12:50.740
in the Fiscal Analysis section
for the Research and Statistics

00:12:50.740 --> 00:12:52.110
Division.

00:12:52.110 --> 00:12:55.040
That said, she's also served
in the Treasury Department,

00:12:55.040 --> 00:12:58.050
and on the White House's
Council of Economic Advisers.

00:12:58.050 --> 00:13:00.340
Louise's research focuses
on health spending

00:13:00.340 --> 00:13:02.080
and other fiscal issues.

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:05.220
She is Harvard squared,
having received her PhD

00:13:05.220 --> 00:13:09.150
in Economics from Harvard, as
well as an undergraduate degree

00:13:09.150 --> 00:13:11.290
in Biology from Harvard.

00:13:11.290 --> 00:13:14.430
Third, we have Claudia Goldin,
the Henry Lee professor

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:16.950
of Economics at Harvard, and
director of the National Bureau

00:13:16.950 --> 00:13:19.550
of Economic Research's
Development of the American

00:13:19.550 --> 00:13:21.300
Economy program.

00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:24.480
Claudia is an economic
historian and a labor economist.

00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:26.430
She has received many
honors and awards that

00:13:26.430 --> 00:13:28.550
are just far too
numerous to name here,

00:13:28.550 --> 00:13:30.760
so you can look up on Google.

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:33.180
Her research has covered
a wide array of topics,

00:13:33.180 --> 00:13:36.470
including slavery, the
economic impact of war,

00:13:36.470 --> 00:13:40.090
the female labor force,
immigration, New Deal policies,

00:13:40.090 --> 00:13:43.430
income inequality,
technological change, education,

00:13:43.430 --> 00:13:45.640
and the gender gap in pay.

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:47.930
Most of her research
interprets the present

00:13:47.930 --> 00:13:50.630
through the lens of the past,
and explores the origins

00:13:50.630 --> 00:13:52.860
of current issues of concern.

00:13:52.860 --> 00:13:54.360
Claudia earned her
Bachelor's Degree

00:13:54.360 --> 00:13:56.360
from Cornell
University, and a PhD

00:13:56.360 --> 00:13:58.440
from the University of Chicago.

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:02.650
Last, but not least, I'm pleased
to introduce Douglas Elmendorf,

00:14:02.650 --> 00:14:04.800
the dean of the school
that I shall name here,

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:06.890
Harvard Kennedy
School of Government.

00:14:06.890 --> 00:14:09.830
Where he also serves
as the Don K. Price

00:14:09.830 --> 00:14:12.044
professor of Public Policy.

00:14:12.044 --> 00:14:14.460
Doug served as director of the
Congressional Budget Office

00:14:14.460 --> 00:14:18.290
from January 2009
through March 2015.

00:14:18.290 --> 00:14:20.940
Prior to joining CBO, he
served in many positions

00:14:20.940 --> 00:14:24.160
in Washington, including at
the Brookings Institution,

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:25.750
the Council of
Economic Advisers,

00:14:25.750 --> 00:14:28.410
the Treasury Department, and
the Federal Reserve Board.

00:14:28.410 --> 00:14:31.450
He has worked on important
issues, such as budget policy,

00:14:31.450 --> 00:14:34.600
health care, the macroeconomic
effects of fiscal policy,

00:14:34.600 --> 00:14:38.090
social security income security
programs, financial markets,

00:14:38.090 --> 00:14:39.975
and macroeconomic analysis.

00:14:39.975 --> 00:14:41.350
Doug earned his
Bachelor's Degree

00:14:41.350 --> 00:14:44.640
from Princeton University,
and his PhD from Harvard.

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:46.770
So David, I will turn
things over to you.

